title: For Sale/Trade:  Pristine vintage Ruger MKI .22, like new in original box.
postcontent:
I have a nice collectors' grade Ruger Standard Model (Commonly referred to as a MKI, though that designation was only officially used by Ruger on the original longer-barreled target version to distinguish it from the Standard Model. After the MKII and MKIII came out, people began to use the term MKI to describe pre-MKII pistols.)

This gun is in 100% pristine condition inside and out. It looks like it shipped from the Sturm-Ruger factory yesterday. It is in the original red cardboard box which is serialized to the gun with the original brown anti-corrosion wax paper and original manual inside. You don't see them in this condition often. Based on the serial number (14-98xx), this one was manufactured in 1977.

While I personally wouldn't fire the gun and put any wear on it, I have 300+ rounds of Federal JHP .22 ammo and a new production spare factory magazine that will go with the gun.

Rather than sell for cash, I'd much rather prefer to trade for a very basic AK-47. I'd be happy with a Romanian WASR-10 or something similar for a project build. Condition doesn't matter as long as it is free of corrosion and is a stamped receiver with a fixed stock (standard rear stock trunion).

postcontent:
For sale: Remington Model 700 BDL, 30-06. This is the BDL model with hinged floor plate.

The BDL is an upgraded model and includes a high gloss checkered walnut stock with a black fore end tip and black cap on the BDL pistol grip, rich deep bluing for beauty and protection, and hinged floor plate so you can unload the rifle with ease. The hinged plate is nice when its bitter cold and you are trying to unload the gun in the dark, Safer too. (The ADL models do not have this floor plate and you must run your loaded ammo through the chamber to extract. I don’t like that!)

Fun to shoot and very accurate!

See Chuck Hawks review of Remington Model 700 Rifles: http://www.chuckhawks.com/rem_700.htm. Do your own internet research on Remington model 700 in the 30-06 caliber. It gets a lot of great reviews. One of the quotes I often read was “it is one of the most accurate out of the box rifles”.

I emailed Remington with the serial number, 94XXX. They responded that this gun was made in 1964, and this is the only information they have on it.

This was my father’s gun. He bought it new. He lived in the high Sierra mountains in California and deer hunted with it (and did very well!). Other then actual shots on deer, he shot 5 rounds or less each season to make sure it was sighted in. He was from the old school and was a firm believer that if he could not place his shots with iron sights, he should not take a shot. He never used a scope! When I was much younger, I did try deer hunting one year using this rifle, but did not get a shot off. I am a revolver guy now and I do not hunt anymore, so I do not need this 30-06.

Excellent condition. Email me if you want to see more pictures.

First "I'll take it" gets it. If no interest, off it goes to Gunbroker or ?.

$350 plus you pay shipping and associated cost from my FFL to your FFL if this would be required. Price includes a Remington gun case.

title: For Sale:  LNIB Glock 26 9mm
postcontent:
Ok folks, I have a Glock Model 26 up for sale.  She is literally brand new, less than one magazine shot threw her, only 10 rounds or so... WOW!

I call her my “Pocket Glock” or “Baby Bam Bam“ since she is Glock’s smallest pistol.  I mean she is so compact in size, and so light in weight, I qualify the term “pocket Glock”!

This Model 26 the perfect tooth for carrying in a good pocket holster. While it will ride comfortably in a pocket, it is even better suited to concealed carry in a good belt holster.

The Model 26 weighs in at about 21.5 ounces empty, is about six and one-half inches in length and four inches high. In overall size, it is about the same as a pocket .38 Special revolver, but offers over twice the loaded ammunition capacity. This 26 holds ten shots of 9mm ammo in its magazine, for a loaded capacity of eleven.

Like all Glock pistols, my Baby is as reliable as a mechanical device can be. She is flawless and as far as reliability, everything you will ever want in a defensive pistol. The Glock is one of the very few pistols that I would grab and rely upon without extensive testing. 

These type of guns have an enviable track record, especially the 9mm Glocks. Oh, and trust me, she is an easy pistol to learn to shoot well... The trigger pull is relatively easy to learn, and there are no external safeties to manipulate.... To fire this little bitch, you simply pull the trigger.  Honestly, if I was going to Mars and there were hostiles, I would be grabbing a Glock and an AK... think about it.  Both work through mud, sleet, snow... you name it,


The Glock is also easy to disassemble and reassemble for maintenance, without the use of tools.

The 26 shown here is exactly how I like my coffee... strong and all black! 

This 26 comes in a hard case, with two magazines, a magazine loader, which is a welcome tool when trying to fully load the magazine, and is oiled up with the best custom gun oil on the market ZOMBIE BLOOD. The frame is contoured and textured for a good hold, even with wet hands or while wearing gloves.

Actually guys, get this.  She will take any of the Glock 9mm line mags... 10,12, 17, or even the 33 round mag will fit this firearm!!  Simply stating any mag that will fit any Glock 9mm will fit this firearm

Many folks look with disdain upon the 9mm as a defensive cartridge. As a retired Chicago Police officer and range instructor, I do not... 98% of the world carry a 9mm in there military services?   

I often carry a 9mm auto pistol.  As with any handgun in a fight, you should shoot quickly and shoot often, and make sure that the bullets land where intended. Eleven 9mm hollow points will pretty much solve any social situation that can be solved with a handgun.

The shooting world is now flush with small 9mm auto pistols. The Glock is not the smallest nor the lightest available, but it is built to last. Additionally, she is just as strong and just as durable as the full size Glocks.

Glock now has something like around thirty different models, but the Model 26 remains my favorites. It is not the newest, the fanciest, nor the most powerful, but it is one of the handiest and most useful Glock models available, especially for concealed carry.

I am a retired Chicago Police firearms instructor with seven years experience on the range as a Lead Instructor. I am listing this firearm as a Private sale however, I have no problem shipping to any FFL of your choice. Make sure he will take a private sale. If he won’t find another FFL... There are plenty listed on through a google search who will except a private sales in your area.

Tell the FFL I will include a copy of my Drivers License., A photo of my Police retired ID and a copy of my Illinois FOID card.

Buy with confidence, and feel free to ask for feedback as I can give a slew of references... always 100% seller feedback.

I will only ship UPS Ground to the lower 48 states, 

Good luck to the luck and thanks for looking

Winchester M12, 12 gauge, 1955. Cutts Compensator installed at the time - 1955. Includes a Lyman 725 choke, and a Cutts-Lyman Adjustable choke. Lots of birds taken with this gun. Roughly 60% finish. REDUCED to $375

Ruger SP101 in .357. Stainless, Hogue grips, 3 1/4" bbl. 98%. Slight carry wear - minor surface scratches - can send pics. Reduced to $450

Ammo. 9mm, PMP 115gr FMJ, unopened boxes. 500 rounds. Reduced to $100, all or none.

title: For Sale/Trade:  SOLD SOLD SOLD Very Rare Harrison and Richardson .38 Break top Police Revolver
postcontent:
SOLD SOLD SOLD SODL SODL SOLD

This is a very cool little revolver I found at a yard sale and have decided to sell.

This is a H&R .38 S&W black powder catridge (NOT .38 Special) break top 5 shot police pocket revolver. It is a copy of the Smith and Wesson 5 shot revolver of the period. It is extremely rare to see one in .38 instead of .32. Only 10,000 made of this model.

It is in 65-70% original condition with the original nickel plated finish and original hard rubber grips. Amazing for over 100 years old.

It's last patent date is 1896, but the serial number dates it to 1903. So, technically it is considered a modern firearm. It is not registered to anyone and a Red Ryder BB gun is more of a menace to society.

This is the same model revolver that was used in the attempted assassination of Teddy Roosevelt!!!

The sights are basically microscopic and don't really have a purpose. And the grips were made for someone with really small hands. Max effective range of 10 feet.

It is missing all of the internal parts that hold the hammer back, and advance the cylinder. The trigger swings free, and the main spring is present. The missing parts are about $50 online.

It will fire in its current condition, but I don't recommend it without the guts installed. Excellent display piece in its current condition.

I WILL SHIP ANYWHERE IN THE USA- NO FFL TRANSFER NECESSARY. Shipping is $15 with full insurance and tracking

Looking for $150 OBO or trade for the stuff below.
